metadata.name: EYES #88
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #19
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: a house divided #48
metadata.description:
This piece reuses the same line drawing algorithm from 'this is where i draw the line', meant to emulate a marker drawing on paper.

In terms of composition, we start with a single square, which we divide into two rectangles, either horizontally or vertically. We then repeat this process some number of times for each of the resulting rectangles. Finally, we fill the rectangles by drawing them with lines. These lines
can be either straight or curved.

The collection of inks and papers has also been expanded from 'this is where i draw the line'. Collectors of that piece have been placed on the reserve list as a thank you for their support.

This piece was created using p5.js

metadata.name: String art generator #78
metadata.description:
Generative image with animation (1024x1024px) Vanilla JS

This project is a string-art simulator which weaves some patterns in different layouts to make beautiful compositions which can be played from the beginning.
The main features of this generative collection are the several Patterns and Layouts which combined make a huge amount of variations.

“Pattern” defined as the instructions that the thread has to follow to weave the result.
"Layout" defined as the setup of the nails on the board.

The thread is always continuous without interruptions.

Features:

Pattern (21)
Layout (10)
Palette (25)
Layout Mirror (None, Horizontal, Vertical)
ThreadType: (Silk, Wool)
ThreadThickness: (Regular, Thick)

Controls:

[P] Play. 
[R] Result.
[U] Undo. 
[N] Nails. Show/Hide the nails.

[S] Download snapshot (may be slow or unresponsive)

You can weave yourself
Click to change the thread color

This project is an homage to Mary Everest Boole who, more than 100 years ago, used string art to teach math to children.

metadata.name: Landscapes in my mind #23
metadata.description:
In this work I tried to convey the idea of a landscape (many landscapes) with hills, trees, grass, bushes, skies and clouds. As is normal on fxhash I have accomplished all this by writing the code that generates the elements in a scene.
While writing the code to obtain these landscapes I did not try to reproduce landscapes seen in reality or in photography, rather I followed from time to time ideas of landscapes that came to my mind as a sort of lucid dream. I hope I managed to convey this idea of a landscape that is halfway between reality and fantasy.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with recursive functions an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density could be homogeneous (land heightmap drive the density) or biased to have more density towards the top, bottom, left or right of the land.


Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[1] to render at 1600x1600
[2] to render at 2400x2400
[3] to render at 3200x3200
[s] to save a png at last rendered resolution.


Features:
"LandPalette": 20 colormaps
"TreePalette": 20 colormaps
"Light":  Morning, Evening, Night
"SkyColor": Blue, Azure, Turquoise, Gray, VioletRed
"Haze": True, False
"Rainbow":  True, False
"Grayscale": True, False
"TreeDensity": Homogeneous, Top, Bottom, Left, Right

metadata.name: Sand Shapes #74
metadata.description:
An experiment in line texture by Nate Donato, this piece features lines composed of a sand-like particle texture.  Bounds around line generation properties were set loosely, resulting in many possible line characters with unique weights, wobbles, and more.  Lines are generated in individual layered segments one by one, resulting in a pleasing animation of gradual composition as they compose one of twelve possible shapes, in one of eight possible color schemes.  

Each "line" is made up of thousands of points, and so rendering the live view of this piece may be computer intensive.  As an added bonus a small amount of proprietary line data is emitted to the development console, allowing the minted collection to serve as a palette of potential line qualities for the artist to use in future works.  Any owners of pieces used in this way by the artist on future projects will be granted a share of said future project's royalties.

In active live view, press [1] to view medium res, [2] to view high res, and [0] to return to original viewport width view.

Written in vanilla JavaScript without the use of external libraries.
